explanation: To check whether OS_BinSemTake violates the MISRA rule forbidding use of memcmp to compare null-terminated strings you must inspect the functions it calls (and their callees) for any use of memcmp on C strings. • OS_ObjectIdGetById — direct callee from OS_BinSemTake; must be examined for any memcmp use or string comparisons on tokens/IDs. • OS_BinSemTake_Impl — direct callee when ObjectIdGetById succeeds; its body (and callees) may perform comparisons that could use memcmp. • OS_ObjectIdTransactionInit, OS_ObjectIdToArrayIndex, OS_ObjectIdConvertToken, OS_ObjectIdTransactionCancel — direct callees of OS_ObjectIdGetById; include these because ObjectIdGetById may delegate string/ID comparisons to them. Any memcmp misuse could occur in these helpers. • OS_GenericBinSemTake_Impl — callee of OS_BinSemTake_Impl; include to cover implementation-specific comparisons performed in the generic implementation. • memcmp — the standard library function in question; include its symbol so the analyzer can find all uses/calls and check argument provenance (whether the compared objects are null-terminated strings).  Inspecting this set of symbols covers the call chain from OS_BinSemTake to places where memcmp might be invoked on string data.
